                    encompasses a broad category of specialized vehicles designed to recover and transport disabled, damaged, or illegally parked vehicles. These trucks come in various configurations, including flatbed, wheel-lift, hook-and-chain, and boom tow trucks, each suited to specific towing scenarios.

                    Tow trucks are equipped with robust t");
            WriteLiteral(@"owing mechanisms, such as winches, hydraulic lifts, or booms, to handle a range of vehicle types. A common use of tow trucks is roadside assistance, where they are deployed to help stranded drivers with vehicles that have broken down. They are also frequently used in accident recovery, parking enforcement, and vehicle impoundment operations.

                    Modern tow trucks often include advanced features such as rear-view cameras, wireless controls, and GPS systems. These technologies enhance the precision and efficiency of towing operations, allowing drivers to recover vehicles safely even in challenging conditions, such as narrow streets or busy highways.

                    One of the most recognizable types of tow trucks is the hook-and-chain tow truck, which uses chains to secure the vehicle. While this design is effective, it is less commonly used today because it can damage the towed vehicle. More contemporary designs, such as wheel-lift tow trucks, use a hydraulic lift to raise the vehicle");
            WriteLiteral(@" by its tires, reducing the risk of damage.

                    Tow trucks play an essential role in keeping roads safe and operational. They provide crucial support during emergencies, clear accident scenes, and help enforce parking regulations. Their reliability and adaptability make them an indispensable part of vehicle recovery operations.
                </p>

